131: The Takama languages are a small language family spoken in Papua New Guinea
They consist of two languages, Takia and Arapesh
Takia is spoken on Karkar Island and has approximately 40,000 speakers
Arapesh is spoken on the mainland and has around 30,000 speakers
Both languages belong to the Torricelli language family
The Takama languages are agglutinative, with a system of suffixes and prefixes used to indicate grammatical relationships
They have a relatively simple phonology, with a small number of consonant and vowel sounds
The vocabulary of the Takama languages is not well-documented, but they appear to have borrowed words from other languages in the region, including Tok Pisin and English
